WELCOME TO THE

Utah Geological Survey's

Rockhounder Web Application


Collecting Rules


Utahs rock, mineral, and fossil collectors must adhere to rules and regulations established by owners or managing agencies of the lands on which they wish to collect.


Utahs lands are managed by the federal government (Bureau of Land Management, U.S. Forest Service, National Park Service, Bureau of Reclamation, U.S. Department of Defense, U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service, American Indians), state government (Utah School and Institutional Trust Lands Administration), and private owners (including local governments). Rockhounding permits may be required to collect on some government lands, and permission is required to collect on private lands.
Utah Geological Survey

Rockhounding Resources

Below you will find detailed information on rockhounding in Utah including rules and regulations, safety tips, and identification resources. Also, check out some of our most popular rock, mineral, and fossil articles and destination ideas to get out and explore.

Rock, Mineral, and Fossil Collecting Rules

Good stewardship of the land requires proper rockhounding etiquette. Depending on your location and the land ownership, additional permits may be required from State and/or local agencies. Respect private property rights and do not trespass. The description of a site in this application does not constitute permission for you to collect on the site. It is your responsibility to determine the actual status of the land and contact the appropriate person or agency for permission. Detailed rules and regulation by agency can be found here.


  • FEDERAL LANDS: About 67 percent of Utahs lands are managed by the federal government. Most of this land is open to collecting except for National Parks, most National Monuments, American Indian lands, military reservations, dam sites, and wildlife refuges.


  • STATE LANDS: Most state-owned property is managed by the School and Institutional Trust Lands Administration (Trust Lands) and a rockhounding permit is required to collect on these lands. A fee is charged for the annual permit.


  • PRIVATE LANDS: To access or collect on privately owned lands, collectors must contact and obtain permission from the owners prior to entering the property.

Safety Tips

  • When working with tools, wear protective equipment when working with tools such as eye protection, gloves, and a hard hat.


  • Do not work alone and let someone else know your schedule.


  • Carry a first aid kit, sun protection, and plenty of water.


  • Watch for others and when on slopes never work directly above or below anyone.

  • Do not enter abandoned mines or shafts.

Take Note

  • Dinosaur and other vertebrate fossils may not be collected on any federal or state lands except by permits issued to accredited institutions.


  • The collection of projectile points, pottery, or any other archeological resource or artifact is not allowed without a permit. Projectile points include arrowheads and any prehistoric human-modified stone.


  • Do not use blasting materials and/or firearms in collecting areas. 

  • Only remove small reasonable amounts of material for personal use.

WEB APPLICATION

As you utilize the Rockhounder Application to learn about the collection of rock, mineral, and fossil resources in Utah, it is important to acknowledge the historical and ongoing cultural ties to the lands you are exploring.


All of the cited collection areas are located on public land carved out of the traditional ancestral homelands of indigenous communities. Eight distinct tribal nations exist within the State of Utah, with many additional sovereign nations and cultures maintaining connection since time immemorial to the lands and resources found in this region. 


Take some time to learn more about the regional history and be mindful of your impact. We encourage you to visit the Native Places Atlas compiled by the American West Center at the University of Utah. This growing resource helps record and restore native place names to major landscape features and selected historical and cultural sites in the state.


The Utah Geological Survey asks users of the Rockhounder Application to protect and respect the cultural and spiritual significance of these lands while visiting rockhounding sites. Tribal, State, and Federal Antiquity Laws (16 U.S.C. 470) prohibit the collection of any cultural or archaeological artifacts. If you encounter any cultural or historical artifacts while rockhounding on public lands please leave them undisturbed, document the location, and report to the appropriate land management agency.


ADDITIONAL RESOURCES:

Tribal Nations of Utah, Utah Division of Indian Affairs

Utah Archaeology, Bureau of Land Management

Archaeological Resources Protection Act, United States Code

Tribal Connections Map Viewer, U.S. Forest Service

Land Acknowledgement Statement

Rocks

Under the three different rock types, sedimentary, igneous, and metamorphic, many rocks can be identified using color, texture, grain size, and many other observations. Read What are Igneous, Sedimentary, & Metamorphic Rocks? to learn about the common rock types or contact a UGS geologist to get help identifying your find!


ADDITIONAL RESOURCES:

  • How Do Geologists Know How Old a Rock is?
  • What Kind of Rock Makes a Good Wall?
  • Igneous, Metamorphic, and Sedimentary Rocks in Wasatch Front Canyons

Minerals

There are over 4,000 known minerals, and approximately 80 to 100 new ones are discovered each year. Of all these, only a few hundred are considered common. To help with identification, geologists must look closely at the physical properties of a mineral. These properties can include: color, streak, hardness, cleavage, specific gravity, crystal form, and others. Feel free to contact a UGS geologist to get help identifying your find!


ADDITIONAL RESOURCES:

  • How Do Geologists Identify Minerals?
  • Field Specimens vs. Museum Specimens

Fossils

Fossilsremains, traces, or imprints of past plant and animal life are widely found throughout Utah. Depending on land ownership, some fossils (such as invertebrates and plants) can be collected for personal non-commercial use. However, dinosaur and other vertebrate fossils may NOT be collected on any federal or state lands except by permits issued to accredited institutions. Whether you can keep a fossil or not depends on the type of fossil, and who owns or manages the land where the fossil was found. For more information on collecting and identifying fossils, contact the land managing agency or the Paleontology Section at the Utah Geological Survey, (801) 537-3300.


ADDITIONAL RESOURCES:

  • What Should You Do If You Find a Fossil?
  • Rock, Mineral, and Fossil Collecting Rules
  • Permit Application for Paleontological Investigations

Meteorites

Twenty-seven meteorite finds in Utah are listed in the Meteoritical Societys Meteoritical Bulletin Database. Most likely there are meteorite finds and falls in Utah that are not reported. Meteorite numbers in neighboring states range from 215 in New Mexico to 6 in Idaho. The odds of finding a meteorite are slim even if you see it fall. Most disintegrate before reaching the ground.


ADDITIONAL RESOURCES:

  • Meteorite or Meteorwrong?
  • Have Meteorites or Meteorite Craters Been Found in Utah?
  • More Meteorite Information, Washington University, St. Louis, MO
  • A Comprehensive Guide to Meteorite Identification, Aerolite Meteorites, Tucson, AZ
  • Do I Have a Meteorite?, Center for Meteorite Studies, Arizona State University
  • Utahs Clark Planetarium has a few meteorite experts. Contact them for help identifying a find.

Artifacts

Artifacts are any objects made by a human that is more than 50 years old. This definition includes the arrowheads and pottery sherds that are commonly found on prehistoric sites in Utah, and also extends to metal nails and glass insulators from historical sites. The removal of artifacts and the disturbance of archaeological sites (both prehistoric and historical) is illegal under both federal and state laws. If you believe you have found something significant, take a photo of it and record where you found it (GPS is great if you have one) and let the land managing agency know.


ADDITIONAL RESOURCES:

  • What Prehistoric and Contemporary Indigenous People Were in Utah?
  • What Do I Do If I Discover Damage to an Archaeological Site?
  • Historic Artifacts Guide, Division of State History
